<bibRefCitation id="EFC18EEEFFCFF13F42E46AF3FE6AF83A" author="Ashmead, W. H." box="[235,413,1943,1969]" pageId="6" pageNumber="507" pagination="73 - 76" refId="ref10063" refString="Ashmead, W. H. (1887) Studies on the North American Proctotrupidae with descriptions of new species from Florida. Entomologica Americana, 3, 73 - 76." type="journal article" year="1887">Ashmead 1887</bibRefCitation>
). After that, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC18EEEFFCFF13F403E6AF3FD13F83A" author="Wheeler, W. M." box="[561,740,1943,1969]" pageId="6" pageNumber="507" refId="ref13544" refString="Wheeler, W. M. 1928. The social insects: their origin and evolution. Harcourt Brace and Co., New York, 378 p. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 140774" type="book" year="1928">Wheeler (1928)</bibRefCitation>
reared this species in a laboratory and was able to get both apterous and, more rarely, macropterous females, and both macropterous and even more rarely apterous males. The diagnoses of the male and the macropterous female are based on figures of 
